{
    "analysis": "Previous metric-level anomaly detection returned many (dozens of) component-KPI groups with anomaly_count equal to all points in-window (31) and earliest_anomaly_timestamp at 2021-03-04 00:30:00+0800. Examples include IG01/IG02/MG01/MG02 JVM heap-related KPIs (HeapMemoryMax, NoHeapMemoryUsed, etc.), various OSLinux process/network KPIs, and others. However, many of these are likely false positives: several KPIs are constant maxima (e.g., HeapMemoryMax equals the configured heap and thus global_p95 == max_value_in_window) or the observed breach over the global P95 is negligible. According to the fault-identification rules, we must exclude KPIs where the maximum in the fault sub-series only slightly exceeds the threshold (threshold breach <= 50% of extremal) or where the metric is essentially constant and equals the threshold. To proceed, we should filter the metric anomalies to keep only groups whose in-window max value significantly exceeds their global P95 (use severity = (max_value_in_window - global_p95) / global_p95 and keep severity > 0.5). This will narrow to plausible faults for subsequent trace and log analysis. The next atomic step is to run this filtering and return a compact list of candidate faults with severity ratios and counts so we can localize the root cause component and occurrence time.",
