{
    "analysis": "Metrics analysis found no resource KPI with a significant breach (no metric groups passed severity > 50%), so metrics did not produce a clear single faulty component. Trace analysis, however, found clustered anomalies in call counts around 00:31–00:35 UTC+8 involving IG01/IG02 -> Tomcat01, MG02 <-> Tomcat02, MG01 -> dockerA1/dockerB1, and other call links. Log analysis shows elevated GC pause metrics for Tomcat01 (earliest anomaly 00:32) and Tomcat02 (earliest anomaly 00:31) and some log.row_count spikes. There are no error_log entries in the incident window. From the rules: when multiple service-level faults exist, the root cause is the most downstream faulty service in a trace; logs (GC pause) point to Tomcat services having workload/latency issues near the trace anomalies. To localize the root cause we must (1) parse trace anomaly groups to identify partner services and direction (which service is downstream in each anomalous call chain) and the earliest anomaly time per pair, and (2) inspect Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 log anomalies (gc_pause_max and row_count) to see which Tomcat shows the earliest and most severe behavioral deviation. This will allow choosing the most downstream faulty service and exact occurrence time. The next step is therefore to extract parsed trace-direction information for the top trace anomaly groups and to fetch the per-timestamp log anomaly records for Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 (gc_pause_max and row_count) inside the incident window so we can compare earliest timestamps and severity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace anomaly table (use global P95 from full series and incident-window filtered rows), retrieve the top 20 trace anomaly groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc. For each group, parse the trace_name to extract: direction ('to' if name contains 'to_<Component>' or 'from' if contains 'from_<Component>') and partner_component (the target or source component name that appears after 'to_' or 'from_'). Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, direction, partner_component. Limit to 20 rows.\nAdditionally, for log anomalies, filter log.csv to the incident window and return all rows (limit 50) for cmdb_id in [Tomcat01, Tomcat02] where log_name is in ['log.gc_pause_max','log.row_count'] and value >= global_p95 (use the global_p95 computed from full series). Return columns: cmdb_id, log_name, timestamp, value, global_p95. Limit to 50 rows and sort by timestamp asc.",
}

{
    "analysis": "From previous steps: global P95 thresholds were computed from full series. Metric analysis produced no high-severity resource KPI faults (no metric group passed severity > 50%). Trace analysis found clustered call-count anomalies around 00:31–00:35 UTC+8 implicating calls to/from Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 among others. Log analysis found GC pause spikes for Tomcat02 (earliest anomaly 00:31) and Tomcat01 (earliest anomaly 00:32), and some log.row_count spikes. No error_log entries exist in-window. According to the localization rules, we must (1) identify which service is the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chains and (2) determine the earliest occurrence time of the fault from the first anomalous point of that service's faulty KPI. To decide between Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 (both showing anomalies in traces/logs), we need per-timestamp evidence: the first timestamp where each candidate group's value exceeds its global P95 and the timeline of related trace events. Therefore we must extract per-timestamp trace rows related to Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 (to_/from_ trace entries) in the incident window and the per-timestamp log entries for Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 for the relevant log KPIs (log.gc_pause_max and log.row_count), compute each group's earliest anomaly timestamp (value >= global P95), and return compact tables so we can compare earliest times and decide the most downstream faulty service and exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and per (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available series (do NOT recalculate using only the incident window). Then filter rows to the incident window 2021-03-04 00:30:00 to 2021-03-04 01:00:00 (UTC+8).\n1) Trace extraction: select all trace.csv rows in-window where trace_name contains 'to_Tomcat01','from_Tomcat01','to_Tomcat02', or 'from_Tomcat02'. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group return per-timestamp rows with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, global_p95. Also compute for each group the earliest timestamp where value >= global_p95 (earliest_anomaly_timestamp). Return the per-group earliest_anomaly_timestamp summary (one row per group) and also the full per-timestamp rows limited to 50 rows sorted by timestamp asc.\n2) Log extraction: for log.csv, filter to cmdb_id in [Tomcat01, Tomcat02] and log_name in ['log.gc_pause_max','log.row_count']. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global_p95 (from full series), then return per-timestamp rows in-window with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value, global_p95. Also compute earliest_anomaly_timestamp per group where value >= global_p95. Return the per-group earliest_anomaly summary (one row per group) and up to 50 per-timestamp rows sorted by timestamp asc.\nLimit each returned per-timestamp table to 50 rows. If a group has no in-window row meeting value >= global_p95, indicate no anomaly for that group in the summary. Return compact tables only (no raw full series beyond the 50-row limits)."
}

